The cartesian product, also known as the cross product, is a mathematical operation that combines two sets to create a new set. It creates all possible ordered pairs by taking one element from each set.

Formally, the cartesian product of two sets A and B is denoted as A x B and is defined as:

A x B = {(a, b) : a ∈ A and b ∈ B}

For example, let A = {1, 2} and B = {3, 4}. The cartesian product A x B would be:

A x B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

In this case, each element in set A is combined with each element in set B to create a new set of ordered pairs.

